%U A397562 52,56,60,50,55,47,53,57,58,59,61,62,65,66,63,69,67,70
%N A397562 Lexicographically earliest sequence of distinct positive integers such that for any prime number p, the absolute difference of the p-adic valuations of two consecutive terms is at most 1.
%C A397562 In other words, for any n > 0, the numerator and denominator of a(n+1)/a(n) are squarefree.
%C A397562 This sequence can be seen as a variant of A326927 with kings instead of knights.
%C A397562 Will every positive integer appear in the sequence?
%C A397562 A003557(a(n)) divides a(n-1) (provided that n > 1) and a(n+1).
%H A397562 Rémy Sigrist, <a href="/A397562/b397562.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%H A397562 Rémy Sigrist, <a href="/A397562/a397562.gp.txt">PARI program</a>
